{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:37:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"416"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/416"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.62,0.15,0.11,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"416"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115999"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/416"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"416"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97995"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49596"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115999"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of right upper quadrant pain. The pain was constant in nature and not associated with any other symptoms. The pain has now resolved. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 154/96 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Examination of the chest and abdomen does not reveal any abnormalities. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholecystitis","Renal cell carcinoma","Adrenal tumour","Hydatid disease of the liver","Abdominal aortic aneurysm"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan demonstrates a right-sided enhancing renal mass with some necrotic areas, consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003E(see image below). There is also evidence of invasion into the inferior vena cava. Renal cell carcinomas are the most common malignant renal tumours arising from the renal tubular epithelium. They are often discovered as incidental findings on imaging studies, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with persistent right upper quadrant pain and is unlikely to resolve within such a short period as described in this patient. Moreover, the gallbladder is not visible in the provided image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is another common incidental finding on CT. However, the adrenal gland is not visible in this image (it would be located higher), and the tumour is clearly originating from the renal parenchyma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid disease of the liver\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as well-defined, encapsulated hepatic cysts on CT scan. These cysts are caused by \u003Cem\u003EEchinococcus\u003C/em\u003E tapeworm and are endemic in certain regions. The image does not show any characteristic liver cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal aortic aneurysms\u003C/strong\u003E are generally asymptomatic and often discovered incidentally on abdominal ultrasound. A CT scan would demonstrate an increased diameter of the aorta, which is not seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that the classical presentation of renal cell carcinoma - a triad of haematuria, loin pain, and a palpable flank mass - is now uncommon, occurring in less than 10% of cases. When present, this triad often indicates advanced disease. The majority of renal cell carcinomas, as in this case, are detected incidentally during imaging studies performed for unrelated reasons. The patient\u0027s transient right upper quadrant pain was likely unrelated to the renal mass but led to the fortuitous discovery of the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Renal cell carcinomas are often asymptomatic and frequently discovered as incidental findings on imaging studies.","The classic triad of painless haematuria, flank mass, and loin pain in renal cell carcinoma is now uncommon and often indicates advanced disease.","CT imaging is crucial for the diagnosis and staging of renal cell carcinoma, showing enhancing renal masses with potential necrotic areas and vascular invasion."],"references":["Gibbons RP, Monte JE, Correa RJ Jr, Mason JT. Manifestations of renal cell carcinoma. Urology. 1976 Sep;8(3):201-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/788291/","Bellin MF, Valente C, Bekdache O, Maxwell F, Balasa C, Savignac A, Meyrignac O. Update on Renal Cell Carcinoma Diagnosis with Novel Imaging Approaches. Cancers (Basel). 2024 May 18;16(10):1926. doi: 10.3390/cancers16101926. PMID: 38792005; PMCID: PMC11120239. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38792005/","Sankineni S, Brown A, Cieciera M, Choyke PL, Turkbey B. Imaging of renal cell carcinoma. Urol Oncol. 2016 Mar;34(3):147-55. doi: 10.1016/j.urolonc.2015.05.020. Epub 2015 Jun 18. PMID: 26094171. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26094171/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97995"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"416"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17971"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22139"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17971"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dee492d1-c185-46cc-a8c6-42ba0c6c084c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dee492d1-c185-46cc-a8c6-42ba0c6c084c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":430}},{"type":"media","id":"22139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22139"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/pFtdC3CVfMa5QiCDsD1pQuHByK54Ol.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/pFtdC3CVfMa5QiCDsD1pQuHByK54Ol.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":430}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97995"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T09:18:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T09:19:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"416"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115999"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a